        <h2>Really quick intro to native advertising</h2>
        <p>
          Let's start by defining what isn't native. Popups, interstitals, banners&mdash;all that annoying shit&mdash;is not native. That's called <strong>display advertising</strong>.
          In an information economy, your attention is capital. So marketers and publishers can take a pretty blunt approach: to literally blast
          you with ads. Sharethrough thinks there's a better way.
        </p>
        <p>
          Native advertising fits the form and function of the site or app that it's on. In a world of feeds, this concept makes
          a lot of sense. Instead of interrupting someone, they can come across content that is supposed to be there. This makes
          for a better experience, which brings the user back to the site, which brings more revenue for the publishers. A nice little
          feedback loop is created.
        </p>
        <p>
          Instead of a static image, native advertising is a <a href="http://nativeadvertising.com/why-a-native-ad-can-blend-in-to-any-site/" target="_blank">collection of components</a>: headline, description, by line, thumbnail. All the same
          atomic units that make up an article in a feed.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <%= image_tag "native-process.png" %>
          <figcaption>
            Really high level model of how native advertising works.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          So it's good for the publisher and the reader but what about the advertiser? Turns out native advertising works better form
          them too. We've <a href="http://www.sharethrough.com/neuroscience/" target="_blank">done some research</a> on this. We've found
          that readers "see" native ads more often than traditional display ads. Viewability rates are the same but the reader <em>actually</em>
          reads the native ad.

        </p>
        <h2>New Performance Reporting</h2>
        <p>
          One of the main jobs of Sharethrough for Publishers (SFP) is to tell publishers how much money they're making.
          Understanding performance drives a lot of engagement and helps publishers become succcessful. One of my first projects was to
          improve our reporting.
        </p>
        <h3>The Problem</h3>
        <p>
          There were two main problems. First, reports should be used to help publishers answer specific questions. The <strong>existing reporting was too broad</strong> and only scratched the surface.
          It was hard to truly understand how well your monetization was doing. Key metrics like fill rates, earnings, and impression
          requests could be answered. But what about understanding fill on a website <strong>as a whole</strong>? Or on a specific device?
          What about the ads themselves? These questions were lost on publishers.
        </p>
        <p>
          Second, once you can answer those questions, <strong>how do you take action</strong> on that knowledge?
        </p>
        <h3>Sketching &amp; Ideation</h3>
        <p>
          The first thing I wanted to understand was the <strong>mental model</strong> of a publisher when they think about performance.
          What metaphors do they use? How do they think about performance.
        </p>
